Concrete Strength Prediction Model by Warren Camp¶

Objective

To predict the concrete strength using the data available in file concrete_data.xls. Apply feature engineering and model tuning to obtain 80% to 95% of R2 score.

Resources Available

The data for this project is available in file https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/concrete/compressive/.

Attribute Information:

Given are the variable name, variable type, the measurement unit and a brief description. The concrete compressive strength is the regression problem. The order of this listing corresponds to the order of numerals along the rows of the database.

Name --Data Type --Measurement --Description

  • Cement(cement) --quantitative --kg in a m3 mixture --Input Variable
  • Blast Furnace Slag (slag) --quantitative --kg ina m3 mixture --Input Variable
  • Fly Ash (ash) --quantitative --kg ina m3 mixture --Input Variable
  • Water (water) --quantitative --kg in a m3 mixture --Input Variable
  • Superplasticizer (superplastic) --quantitative --kg in a m3 mixture --Input Variable
  • Coarse Aggregate (coarseagg) --quantitative --kg in a m3 mixture --Input Variable
  • Fine Aggregate (fineagg) --quantitative --kg in a m3 mixture --Input Variable
  • Age(age) --quantitative --Day (1~365) --Input Variable
  • Concrete compressive strength(strength) --quantitative --MPa --Output Variable

In [63]:
outlier_columns = ['slag', 'water', 'superplastic', 'fineagg', 'age', 'strength']
for f in outlier_columns:
    q3 = df[f].quantile(q = 0.75)
    q2 = df[f].quantile(q = 0.25)
    IRQ = q3 - q2
    upper_bound = q3 + IRQ * 1.5
    arr = df[f].to_numpy()
    print('\n', f, ' outliers include: \n')
    for i in range(len(arr)):
        if (arr[i] > upper_bound):
            print(f, i, arr[i])

Analysis: Based on the boxplots: slag (2 outliers), water (4 outliers), superplastic (10 outliers), fineagg (5 outliers), age (50+outliers ), and strength (4 outliers) contain outliers, where the upper bound is q3 + IRQ * 1.5, see calaculations below. My major concern was with the number of outliers for age. No adjustments were made to the the outliers becasue there values appear to be resonable, at this time. No extreme adnormal values that could affect the model fit were identified.¶

3. Feature Engineering techniques¶

  • Identify opportunities (if any) to extracta new feature from existing features, drop a feature(if required)
  • Get data model ready and do a train test split.
  • Decide on complexity of the model, should it be simple linear model in terms of parameters or would aquadratic or higher degree.

Analysis: There appears two independents classes: age and the mixture. Mixtrue is the amount of cement, slag, water, superplastic. The combination of age and mixture will predict the dependent variavle, strength. The pairplots and the correlation matrix below do not readly idetify any features that can be dropped.¶

Implementing k Fold Cross Validation¶

In [86]:
data = df_coded.to_numpy()
X = data[:,0:8]
y = data[:,8]

X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.50, random_state=1)

number_folds = 10
seed =8

kfold =KFold(n_splits=number_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)

model = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=700, 
    criterion='friedman_mse',                                    
    max_depth=5, 
    learning_rate=0.01, 
    min_samples_split=3,
    max_features=3)
In [87]:
results = cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=kfold)
print(results)
print("Accuracy: %.3f%% (%.3f%%)" % (results.mean()*100.0, results.std()*100.0))
